*Q AND A SECTION**SHIVER MY TIMBERS*/From Tad Spencer/: "Please could you tel=
l me where the phrase /shiver=20
my timbers/ originated?"This is one of those supposedly nautical expressions =
that seem to be=20
better known through a couple of appearances in fiction than by any=20
actual sailors' usage.It's an exclamation that may allude to a ship striking =
some rock or=20
other obstacle so hard that her timbers shiver, or shake, so implying a=20
calamity has occurred. It is first recorded as being used by Captain=20
Frederick Marryat in /Jacob Faithful/ in 1835: "I won't thrash you Tom.=20
Shiver my timbers if I do".It has gained a firm place in the language because=
 almost fifty years=20
later Robert Louis Stevenson found it to be just the kind of old-salt=20
saying that fitted the character of Long John Silver in /Treasure=20
Island/: "Cross me, and you'll go where many a good man's gone before=20
you ... some to the yard-arm, shiver my timbers, and some by the board,=20
and all to feed the fishes". Since then, it's mainly been the preserve=20
of second-rate seafaring yarns.
